We have a project using `SignalR` with high traffic on it, and using events OnConnect/Disconnect to cache some objects based on our logic, there is a `ConcurrentDictionary` as a cache but I can see a few logs in our app insights showing the `TryAdd` method returning `false` as the key already exists. 

It caused some dysfunctionality in our web but after restarting the backend everything became normal.
Here is the code similar to our code base:

```csharp
public class SingletonService
{
    private readonly SemaphoreSlim _semaphore = new SemaphoreSlim(1, 1);
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cancellationTokenSource = new();
    private readonly ConcurrentDictionary<int, string> _cache = new();

    public async Task<string> OnConnectAsync(ParamModel model)
    {
        if (_cache.TryGetValue(model.Key, out var value))
        {
            return value;
        }

        await _semaphore.WaitAsync(_cancellationTokenSource.Token);

        try
        {
            if (_cache.TryGetValue(model.Key, out var inValue))
            {
                return inValue;
            }

            //doing some work
            await Task.Delay(500);

            var added = _cache.TryAdd(model.Key, model.Value);

            if (!added) //<------ We saw this 4 times in 30 days app running
                Console.WriteLine($"------Failed to add key: {model.Key}");

            return model.Value;
        }
        finally
        {
            if (!_cancellationTokenSource.IsCancellationRequested)
                _semaphore.Release();
        }
    }

    public async Task OnDisconnect(ParamModel model)
    {
        if (_cache.TryGetValue(model.Key, out var value))
        {
            if (_cache.TryRemove(model.Key, out var _))
            {
                //doing some work
                await Task.Delay(100);
            }
        }
    }
}
```
Those methods are calling in the SignalR hub for connect/disconnect events. The `model.Key` has only up to 20 unique values.
What can be the issue? 
Is it related to context capturing, so before finishing `await Task.Delay(500)` the Key changed to an existing key?
Or is SingalR triggering `OnConnect` event 2 times at the same time?

I couldn't reproduce the issue.

## Background and Motivation

Previous versions of Razor (`services.AddRazorPages()`) had a `.Conventions` property in the options where you could write conventions to prefix razor pages with, well, a prefix.
This can be very useful in a plugin scenario where you have multiple assemblies (Razor Class Libraries) with their own razor pages, that may have the same paths, and map them with prefixes to prevent path conflicts.
Having a way to prefix the razor pages without manually ensuring there are no conflicting paths would lead to decreased maintenance and development time.

## Proposed API

There are multiple places where this could be added. As mentioned, it could previously be done with conventions in `.AddRazorPages(o => o.Conventions...)`, but as it is directly related to the URL mapping it probably belongs together with `.MapRazorComponents()` in `.UseEndpoints()`.

```
namespace Microsoft.AspNetCore.Builder;

public static class RazorComponentsEndpointConventionBuilderExtensions
    public static RazorComponentsEndpointConventionBuilder AddAdditionalAssembly(
        this RazorComponentsEndpointConventionBuilder builder,
        string urlPrefix,
        Assembly assembly) { }
}
```

## Usage Examples

```
app.UseEndpoints(endpointBuilder =>
{
    var builder = endpointBuilder.MapRazorComponents<App>();
    foreach(IPlugin plugin in plugins)
    {
        builder.AddAdditionalAssembly(
            plugin.GetType().Assembly.GetName().Name,
            plugin.GetType().Assembly)
    }
    builder.AddInteractiveServerRenderMode();
});
```

## Alternative Designs

An alternative could be adding the old `.Conventions` to `services.AddRazorComponents()`.

## Risks

Can't think of any risks of the top of my head with the `.AddAdditionalAssembly()` chaining.

